<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Prep research for the custom-element <code>tagName</code> naming decision
  (<a href="/backlog/841-decide-the-we-contract-custom-element-tag-naming-convention-/">#841</a>) — the
  sibling carved out of the <a href="/backlog/822-enrich-block-cem-with-tagname-attributes-properties-slots-so/">#822</a>
  ruling, under the Block Explorer epic
  (<a href="/backlog/746/">#746</a>). #822 settled that the custom-element surface
  (<code>tagName</code> + attributes/properties/slots) is a <strong>WE-owned contract</strong> and FUI is one
  implementation that conforms (impl-is-not-a-standard + the <a href="/backlog/463/">#463</a>
  polyglot/forward-adapter vision). It deliberately left the one genuine remaining call to this item:
  <strong>what <code>tagName</code> value WE specifies</strong>. The decision binds <strong>only</strong> the
  global-registration modes (static-HTML / global <code>customElements.define</code> / impl-swap); deep
  compile-time / JSX consumption never materializes a runtime global tag, so naming there stays totally
  flexible (most-flexible-default, an invariant #822 already fixed).
</p>

<h2>The tree as it actually is</h2>
<p>
  <code>src/_data/blocks.json</code> (75 blocks) carries <strong>zero</strong> <code>tagName</code> fields
  today, and <code>scripts/gen-cem.mjs</code> emits a CEM custom-element declaration
  (<code>customElement: true</code> + <code>tagName</code>) <strong>only</strong> when a block carries an
  explicit <code>tagName</code> — it <strong>never fabricates</strong> one
  (<a href="https://github.com/">gen-cem.mjs:68-80</a>: <em>"no tag is ever fabricated — <code>registryName</code>
  is a DI registry class name, NOT a custom-element tag"</em>). So <code>gen:cem</code> emits 0 custom-element
  declarations until these values are authored.
</p>
<p>
  The load-bearing finding: <strong>most <code>type:Component</code> blocks are not custom elements at all.</strong>
  Surveying the FUI tree, <strong>only 5 custom <em>elements</em></strong> register via
  <code>customElements.define</code> — <code>auto-heading</code> (block <code>transient-component</code>),
  <code>auto-complete</code> (<code>autocomplete</code>), <code>route-view</code> + <code>route-outlet</code>
  (both from the single <code>router</code> block), and <code>background-tasks</code>
  (<code>background-task-surface</code>). Every other <code>type:Component</code> block registers as a
  <em>behavior / attribute / function</em> (<code>tabs</code>→attributes, <code>stepper</code>→<code>registerStepper</code>,
  <code>tree-select</code>→<code>registerTreeSelect</code>, <code>master-detail</code>→<code>MasterDetailBehavior</code>),
  and everything FUI registers via <code>attributes.define</code> (<code>type-ahead</code>, <code>for-each</code>,
  <code>nav:list</code>, <code>grid:cell-edit</code>, …) is a custom <em>attribute</em>, scoped out by #822.
</p>
<p>Two structural facts fall out, and both reshape the original fork:</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Element-ness is sparse and cannot be inferred from <code>type:Component</code>.</strong> Auto-deriving
    a tag for every Component would fabricate fictional <code>&lt;tabs&gt;</code> / <code>&lt;stepper&gt;</code>
    elements FUI never registers — violating <code>gen-cem</code>'s never-fabricate invariant. Element-ness must
    be <strong>authored / opt-in</strong>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>A block is not 1:1 with a tag.</strong> <code>router</code> (one block) registers <strong>two</strong>
    elements; <code>autocomplete</code>→<code>auto-complete</code> and
    <code>transient-component</code>→<code>auto-heading</code> show tag ≠ id. A pure prefix+id derivation is
    structurally impossible, and the value must be <strong>overridable</strong>; the data model must allow a block
    to declare 0, 1, or N tags.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  FUI's 5 tags are all <strong>bare kebab-case with no vendor prefix</strong> — there is <strong>no
  <code>fui-</code> prefix anywhere</strong>. #822's hypothetical <code>fui-&lt;id&gt;</code> is contrary to both
  FUI's real practice and the constellation: a <code>fui-</code> prefix would brand the WE-owned contract tag with
  the implementation's name (a category error). And <strong>24 single-word component ids</strong>
  (<code>dropdown</code>, <code>menu</code>, <code>dialog</code>, <code>drawer</code>, <code>checkbox</code>, …)
  are <strong>invalid as bare custom-element tags</strong> — the WHATWG "valid custom element name" production
  requires a hyphen — so a <strong>uniform prefix mechanically guarantees validity</strong> across the catalog
  without per-entry renaming.
</p>

<h2>Prior art — how the ecosystem names custom-element tags</h2>
<p>
  The web platform mandates only the <em>shape</em> of a valid name (hyphen-required, lowercase-start, a
  reserved-hyphenated-name denylist: <code>annotation-xml</code>, <code>color-profile</code>,
  <code>font-face</code>, <code>missing-glyph</code>, …) and imposes <strong>no</strong> prefix policy and
  <strong>no</strong> id→tag mapping. WAI-ARIA APG / MDN govern roles and behavior, not element identifiers. So
  the convention is a project policy, and the prior art is the component-library ecosystem, which has converged
  hard on <strong>one short vendor/namespace prefix per library</strong> — to guarantee the hyphen and avoid
  global-registry collisions:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Shoelace / Web Awesome <code>sl-</code> / <code>wa-</code> · Material Web <code>md-</code> · Adobe Spectrum <code>sp-</code></li>
  <li>Microsoft Fluent <code>fluent-</code> · Ionic <code>ion-</code> · Salesforce Lightning <code>lightning-</code> / <code>c-</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Two further platform facts pin the model:</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Custom Elements Manifest</strong> (the format WE ratified as a protocol,
    <a href="/backlog/626/">#626</a>) resolves a tag from the <code>customElements.define('x-foo', …)</code> call
    string, <strong>never</strong> from filename/dirname, and models a module emitting <strong>many</strong>
    declarations — matching the <code>router</code>→2-elements reality and confirming the tag is an authored value
    distinct from the block id.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Scoped custom-element registries</strong> (the <code>ElementInternals</code> / scoped-registry
    proposal) let a tag bind locally rather than globally — the platform analog of #822's "deep JSX consumption
    dissolves the runtime global tag." The convention governs the <strong>global</strong> mode; scoped / compile
    consumption is the always-free path.
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  <strong>Verdict:</strong> a short uniform prefix + the component's kebab name is the dominant, predictable,
  collision-safe scheme; the prefix is a per-library namespace. For WE the namespace is the <strong>standard</strong>
  (<code>we-</code>, aligning with the <code>@webeverything</code> npm scope), not the impl (<code>fui-</code>). The
  id→tag map is authored — opt-in element-ness, override for multi-element/irregular blocks — exactly as CEM models
  it. WE's existing convention authority (<code>docs/agent/conventions.md</code>, machine-checked by
  <code>check:standards</code>) is the home for the new clause, and the prefix is a
  <strong>Config-Extends-Platform-Default</strong> setting (platform default <code>we-</code>; a design-system
  project per <a href="/backlog/746/">#746</a> overrides).
</p>

<h2>What the research reshaped</h2>
<p>
  The item arrived (from #822's carve-out) as a single either/or — <em>derivable convention vs per-entry value</em>.
  The survey splits it into two orthogonal forks plus a configurable dimension the framing omitted:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 1 (new, forced) — element-ness opt-in.</strong> Auto-deriving a tag from <code>type:Component</code>
    is <strong>broken</strong> (fabrication), so element-ness is authored. Default: opt-in.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 2 (original, sharpened) — value-default posture.</strong> Regular derivable convention
    <code>&lt;prefix&gt;-&lt;id&gt;</code> with FUI's 5 names migrating to conform (default, ~75%) vs per-entry
    authored ratifying FUI's existing names.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Supported by default (not a fork) — configurable prefix.</strong> Platform default <code>we-</code>;
    design-system projects override; <code>fui-</code> excluded. The convention binds only global-registration
    modes; compile-time/JSX + DI-override stay totally flexible.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
  Full grounding and the file:line refs in
  <code>reports/2026-06-17-custom-element-tag-naming-convention.md</code>.
</p>
